WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.200 --> 00:00:02.880
CAROLINE: My name
is Caroline and I'm

00:00:02.880 --> 00:00:06.360
delighted to introduce you to
today's speaker, Danny Fields,

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:08.730
in conversation with
Fionnuala Meehan.

00:00:08.730 --> 00:00:13.080
Former manager of The
Ramones, Danny is a music icon

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:16.930
and is widely recognized as
a founding father of punk.

00:00:16.930 --> 00:00:20.000
Fionnuala is a huge music
fan, I've been told,

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.440
and attends the punk rock
festival, Download, every year.

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:27.010
Their conversation will
last about 30 minutes

00:00:27.010 --> 00:00:30.630
and it will be followed by an
audience Q&amp;A, after which Danny

00:00:30.630 --> 00:00:32.580
will be signing
copies of his book

00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:35.330
for those of you who are
here in time to receive one,

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:36.580
just at the side of the stage.

00:00:36.580 --> 00:00:38.288
I think we're in for
a pretty good treat,

00:00:38.288 --> 00:00:39.530
so I'll hand you right over.

00:00:39.530 --> 00:00:40.490
Thank you for coming.

00:00:40.490 --> 00:00:41.490
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Danny.

00:00:41.490 --> 00:00:41.950
DANNY FIELDS: Hello.

00:00:41.950 --> 00:00:43.210
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
Welcome to Dublin.

00:00:43.210 --> 00:00:44.130
Welcome to Ireland.

00:00:44.130 --> 00:00:44.840
DANNY FIELDS: Thank you.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:47.020
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: And
welcome to the Google office.

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:49.450
This is our-- as I was
saying to you earlier--

00:00:49.450 --> 00:00:51.130
this is our EMEA headquarters.

00:00:51.130 --> 00:00:53.530
So not just Irish
people in the audience,

00:00:53.530 --> 00:00:56.350
but people from all
over the region.

00:00:56.350 --> 00:00:58.559
DANNY FIELDS: If I could
see them, I would know that.

00:00:58.559 --> 00:00:59.475
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yes.

00:00:59.475 --> 00:01:00.007
Yeah.

00:01:00.007 --> 00:01:01.090
DANNY FIELDS: [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:06.010
And if you're going like this,
I won't know, so feel free.

00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:08.430
You can stick your
tongues out any time.

00:01:08.430 --> 00:01:09.510
I cannot see you guys.

00:01:09.510 --> 00:01:10.760
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Don't worry.

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:13.060
We'll have plenty of
audience participation later.

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:14.920
So 50 years-- we
were just talking--

00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:16.710
50 years in the music industry.

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:18.053
That's pretty amazing.

00:01:18.053 --> 00:01:23.470
And in looking at your life
across things like journalism,

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:26.640
being an author,
promoter, manager--

00:01:26.640 --> 00:01:29.024
DANNY FIELDS: I have to
scoff at all those words.

00:01:29.024 --> 00:01:30.190
They're kind of [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:31.235
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: They
sound pretty impressive.

00:01:31.235 --> 00:01:32.735
DANNY FIELDS: Yeah,
but we're trying

00:01:32.735 --> 00:01:35.610
to redefine each
one of them in turn.

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:37.714
But, yes, you have
to have a word for--

00:01:37.714 --> 00:01:38.630
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yes.

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:39.360
DANNY FIELDS: OK.

00:01:39.360 --> 00:01:41.570
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: And
so, you don't strike me

00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:43.590
as a person who,
maybe, consciously made

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:45.890
a decision to do a certain
amount of time in each one.

00:01:45.890 --> 00:01:48.549
So how did you end up having
such a fantastic career?

00:01:48.549 --> 00:01:50.090
How did you make
the decision to move

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:51.470
between those different things?

00:01:51.470 --> 00:01:53.470
DANNY FIELDS: Well, when
you have nothing to do,

00:01:53.470 --> 00:01:56.607
you have to do something.

00:01:56.607 --> 00:01:57.190
You know what?

00:01:57.190 --> 00:02:02.210
I'm guided by what I love
to see and who's talented

00:02:02.210 --> 00:02:06.760
and who's beautiful and who says
it great and shoots it great.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:09.289
And is great.

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:09.990
That's it.

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:12.082
And sounds great, of
course-- number one.

00:02:12.082 --> 00:02:13.290
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Number one.

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:15.370
DANNY FIELDS: Or great
songs, number one.

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:22.410
And I was one of-- what
do you do with this kid?

00:02:22.410 --> 00:02:26.150
He's like-- I graduated
from college when I was 19.

00:02:26.150 --> 00:02:28.980
Didn't know-- do
something-- a career--

00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:31.760
I didn't want to be a doctor
like my father, that's

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:33.430
for sure.

00:02:33.430 --> 00:02:36.860
I was not a
business-- certainly,

00:02:36.860 --> 00:02:40.504
for sure, and to this day.

00:02:40.504 --> 00:02:41.920
I answered an ad
in the newspaper.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:44.620
I got a job at a magazine
for teenage girls.

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:47.240
And [SLAP] I was in
the music business.

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:47.740
OK.

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:48.710
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: That's
where it all started.

00:02:48.710 --> 00:02:49.501
DANNY FIELDS: Yeah.

00:02:49.501 --> 00:02:50.690
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yeah.

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:56.470
It's pretty humbling to look
at all of the fantastic artists

00:02:56.470 --> 00:02:59.650
that you've-- some discovered--
worked with over the years.

00:02:59.650 --> 00:03:01.880
I mean, The Doors,
Velvet Underground,

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:05.540
The Ramones, The Stooges.

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:08.210
When you saw these bands
for the first time,

00:03:08.210 --> 00:03:10.899
were you reacting-- was it just
instinct, where you were going,

00:03:10.899 --> 00:03:12.440
yeah, I'm going to
bet on these ones.

00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:13.731
These ones are going to be big.

00:03:13.731 --> 00:03:16.230
How did you-- how did
you make those decisions?

00:03:16.230 --> 00:03:20.010
DANNY FIELDS: When you love
something or someone-- for me,

00:03:20.010 --> 00:03:22.850
the first band I loved
was The Velvet Underground

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:26.540
because they were kind
of our house band.

00:03:26.540 --> 00:03:29.510
They were rehearsing
where we hung out.

00:03:29.510 --> 00:03:31.570
We'd follow them on the road.

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:37.270
And their commercial
destiny was clearly zero.

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:39.630
There's nothing-- no place
you could go with that.

00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:43.020
But we didn't-- you don't
care because you love it.

00:03:43.020 --> 00:03:45.870
And love their songs.

00:03:45.870 --> 00:03:49.055
"Heroin" was the national
anthem of my little unit--

00:03:49.055 --> 00:03:49.870
not the drug.

00:03:49.870 --> 00:03:51.970
The song.

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:57.790
You heard that and you were
defined for the time being

00:03:57.790 --> 00:03:59.390
and you were placed.

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:03.150
And you just stay with them.

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:03.750
Love them.

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:04.430
Stay with them.

00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:09.510
If they break up-- which they
did-- then stay with the ones

00:04:09.510 --> 00:04:12.210
you loved who were
doing the songs, which

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:14.840
for me-- three
musicians from that band

00:04:14.840 --> 00:04:19.000
were subsequently very important
to me, who are Lou Reed, John

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:20.940
Cale, and Nico.

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:25.890
And each of them became--
you get absorbed.

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:28.948
It's the story of life.

00:04:28.948 --> 00:04:32.570
We can't see it from above.

00:04:32.570 --> 00:04:34.220
We can only look at it now.

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:36.980
It's been 50 years, as
you say, and go, oh,

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:38.552
that's what happened.

00:04:38.552 --> 00:04:41.010
Because when it's happening,
you don't know it's happening.

00:04:41.010 --> 00:04:42.280
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yeah.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.810
And can I ask you, of
all of those artists,

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:48.780
maybe who some of
your favorites were?

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:49.280
Is that--

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:50.100
DANNY FIELDS: I
don't like favorites.

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:50.550
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
--an unfair question?

00:04:50.550 --> 00:04:52.370
DANNY FIELDS: I have
so many favorites.

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:53.970
Beethoven is a favorite.

00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:57.950
But I don't want
to hear about him.

00:04:57.950 --> 00:04:59.604
I don't know much about him.

00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:07.620
All those bands were--
would've had careers.

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:09.800
The Ramones would
have been signed,

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:11.680
The Stooges-- in
spite of themselves--

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:13.590
would've been signed.

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:18.310
Nico is the artist I'm
proudest of having something

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:24.320
to do with because she was
thought of as a beauty, which

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:26.630
she hated.

00:05:26.630 --> 00:05:28.590
As much as you can hate
being called a beauty.

00:05:28.590 --> 00:05:29.650
I can't imagine that.

00:05:29.650 --> 00:05:31.390
No one's ever called me that.

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:35.310
But she didn't like
being merely beautiful.

00:05:35.310 --> 00:05:42.320
And she had been through
Brian Jones and Jimmy Page

00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:43.110
in New York.

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:47.640
And her first solo album
was recording songs of her

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:52.300
boyfriends'-- Jackson
Browne and Lou Reed.

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:56.310
But she was writing the
most astonishing songs.

00:05:56.310 --> 00:06:01.150
She was a songwriter and she
worshiped English language

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:02.420
poetry.

00:06:02.420 --> 00:06:05.150
And she would hang
out in my apartment

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:07.950
and look at-- because in
college, I majored in poetry,

00:06:07.950 --> 00:06:13.030
so I had a lot of complete
works of Chaucer and John Donne.

00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:15.910
You all know what
that must look like.

00:06:15.910 --> 00:06:22.710
And she said, oh, I want this
to be the name of my own album.

00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:25.530
And it was a poem by Wordsworth.

00:06:25.530 --> 00:06:28.420
And the phrase was
"The Marble Index."

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:34.690
And this referred to
a bust of Isaac Newton

00:06:34.690 --> 00:06:37.210
in Cambridge that was in marble.

00:06:37.210 --> 00:06:39.020
And had a line in
it-- of course,

00:06:39.020 --> 00:06:40.210
it's not a familiar poem.

00:06:40.210 --> 00:06:43.210
It's not a household
poem at all.

00:06:43.210 --> 00:06:46.910
Contemplating a bust of
Isaac Newton in Cambridge.

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:51.990
And it referred to the
marble index-- marble,

00:06:51.990 --> 00:06:55.630
as in a statue-- of
a mind-- and now I'm

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:58.940
going to get this not exactly
right-- traveling alone

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:02.370
through the universe,
which is Isaac Newton.

00:07:02.370 --> 00:07:06.590
And of course, Nico-- and her
grandiosity and insanity--

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:08.460
identified with that.

00:07:08.460 --> 00:07:11.205
And said, oh, the marble index.

00:07:11.205 --> 00:07:12.250
I said, what?

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:13.290
Is that an album title?

00:07:13.290 --> 00:07:13.890
OK.

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:15.180
Oh, it's Wordsworth.

00:07:15.180 --> 00:07:16.150
Oh, OK, Nico.

00:07:16.150 --> 00:07:18.500
Yeah, you can call it that.

00:07:18.500 --> 00:07:22.810
So bringing her together with
the president of the record

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:27.170
company, she sat on the
floor with a harmonium.

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:33.880
[MIMICS HARMONIUM] And he said,
yes, we've got to sign her.

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:36.820
Get me John Cale on
the phone, quick.

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:44.260
And they did astonishing
collaboration, which was 1968.

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:46.860
It was 100 years
ahead of its time

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:51.940
and will be 100 years ahead
of its time in 2068, 2168.

00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:55.150
That's how amazing
that album was.

00:07:55.150 --> 00:07:56.110
I'm proudest of that.

00:07:56.110 --> 00:07:57.170
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
You're proudest of that.

00:07:57.170 --> 00:07:57.878
DANNY FIELDS: OK.

00:07:57.878 --> 00:08:04.202
Because there's this amazing
songwriter blossoming

00:08:04.202 --> 00:08:06.200
and being recorded as that.

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:09.260
And the amazing
musicianship of John.

00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:11.130
It was two people in
that studio and it

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:13.620
sounds like you have
the Berlin Symphony

00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:14.870
Orchestra or something.

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:16.570
He did it all.

00:08:16.570 --> 00:08:19.710
And I had a feeling that--
from the days of The Velvet

00:08:19.710 --> 00:08:23.240
Underground, they were kind
of waiting to collaborate.

00:08:23.240 --> 00:08:24.130
This was it.

00:08:24.130 --> 00:08:25.850
And that was it.

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:30.200
And my favorite photographer did
the cover shot-- Guy Webster.

00:08:30.200 --> 00:08:32.970
And great album.

00:08:32.970 --> 00:08:33.469
That's it.

00:08:33.469 --> 00:08:34.629
That's number one.

00:08:34.629 --> 00:08:35.049
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: OK.

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:35.770
DANNY FIELDS: Everything else--

00:08:35.770 --> 00:08:36.070
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
That's fantastic.

00:08:36.070 --> 00:08:37.903
DANNY FIELDS: --it
would've happened anyhow.

00:08:37.903 --> 00:08:39.052
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: OK.

00:08:39.052 --> 00:08:42.520
DANNY FIELDS: Not to--
I didn't do anything.

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:44.110
That is the one thing I did.

00:08:44.110 --> 00:08:46.400
I need some of this.

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:48.186
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Let
me pour it for you.

00:08:48.186 --> 00:08:49.280
I'll pour it for you.

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:51.170
DANNY FIELDS: Bear with me.

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:52.420
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: There we go.

00:08:52.420 --> 00:08:54.750
DANNY FIELDS: Yeah,
this was easy.

00:08:54.750 --> 00:08:56.666
OK.

00:08:56.666 --> 00:08:58.290
Ask a question while
I whet my whistle.

00:08:58.290 --> 00:08:58.670
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
I was just going

00:08:58.670 --> 00:09:01.370
to say, while you're pouring
there, I'll ask a question.

00:09:01.370 --> 00:09:05.055
So your book-- it's
a beautiful book.

00:09:05.055 --> 00:09:06.305
DANNY FIELDS: It's a non-book.

00:09:09.230 --> 00:09:12.720
All books are non-books now.

00:09:12.720 --> 00:09:14.385
It's photographs.

00:09:14.385 --> 00:09:16.100
It's photographs.

00:09:16.100 --> 00:09:21.270
It's a book of photographs
that I took of The Ramones

00:09:21.270 --> 00:09:26.720
in the first two years I was
with them as their manager.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:28.720
Because they were perfect
and they came to me

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:30.770
completely formed.

00:09:30.770 --> 00:09:33.174
They were-- there was
nothing I could say.

00:09:33.174 --> 00:09:35.715
Change your hair, or change your
shirt, or change your shoes,

00:09:35.715 --> 00:09:38.130
or change the order
of your songs,

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:42.610
or-- ugh-- change the
bass-- untouchable.

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:44.220
Because they're perfect.

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:46.960
Because I would not have
liked them in the first place

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:50.100
if they had not been perfect.

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:53.630
But-- oh, and you're the manager
and there's nothing to do.

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:55.830
The hotel rooms are
booked, the gig is booked,

00:09:55.830 --> 00:09:56.880
the money's collected.

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:59.021
All that's done.

00:09:59.021 --> 00:09:59.520
Legal.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:01.980
All that's done.

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:04.040
I just started taking
pictures of them

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:06.520
because I was with them.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:10.310
And I had access to
them and I was learning

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:12.920
how to be a photographer.

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:14.420
Just by [CLICK].

00:10:14.420 --> 00:10:18.820
And they're just beautiful.

00:10:18.820 --> 00:10:20.060
They're beautiful pictures.

00:10:20.060 --> 00:10:25.060
And the boys are dead and I
thought this should be a book.

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:28.290
They're just-- I'm
not going to tell you

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:31.562
they're beautiful photographs
it sounds so vain, doesn't it?

00:10:31.562 --> 00:10:33.270
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
But-- no, but they are.

00:10:33.270 --> 00:10:33.400
DANNY FIELDS: But they are.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:35.210
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
They are beautiful.

00:10:35.210 --> 00:10:37.020
DANNY FIELDS: And
it's a limited edition

00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:41.900
by a friend of mine
in Paris, Fabrice

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:45.570
who did a book on Genesis
P-Orridge and a book

00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:46.880
on Marc Almond.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:50.320
Has amazing taste
that goes all over.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:55.070
And he said-- and his partner
Richie Franklin in London--

00:10:55.070 --> 00:10:56.560
so they commute.

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:59.210
And they wanted to do a
book of those photographs.

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:01.210
And I thought, yeah, OK.

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:03.760
And now I'm a
photographer because--

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:04.380
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
Another one [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:05.421
DANNY FIELDS: It says so.

00:11:05.421 --> 00:11:07.520
A book of photographs,
and that's what it is.

00:11:07.520 --> 00:11:12.580
What I had to do-- a photograph
is worth a million words,

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:14.520
or a thousand words--
what's the cliche?

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:16.740
You still have something
to say about it, especially

00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:18.120
if you were there.

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:23.520
And here we see Dee Dee
picks up a piece of shit

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:25.360
on the capitol of
the United States

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:29.240
and puts it on a
balcony and lines

00:11:29.240 --> 00:11:31.720
it up with the Washington
Monument and stands back

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:35.150
and-- you're, OK, it's art.

00:11:35.150 --> 00:11:36.690
Because Dee Dee
was a great artist.

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:38.773
