All right.

00:22:55.685 --> 00:22:56.560
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: OK.

00:22:56.560 --> 00:22:57.670
DANNY FIELDS: We're here
to talk about music.

00:22:57.670 --> 00:22:58.586
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yes.

00:22:58.586 --> 00:23:01.720
Movies where they-- [LAUGHS].

00:23:01.720 --> 00:23:03.377
So you still live in New York?

00:23:03.377 --> 00:23:04.960
DANNY FIELDS: Yes,
I live in New York.

00:23:04.960 --> 00:23:08.000
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yeah, you
would never live anywhere else?

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:11.510
DANNY FIELDS: I would
gladly live anywhere else.

00:23:11.510 --> 00:23:13.570
But I'm forced to live there.

00:23:13.570 --> 00:23:16.100
And it's OK.

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:18.040
It's near-- there are airports.

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:21.620
And I spend a lot
of time in London.

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:24.550
I've been in London five
months this past year,

00:23:24.550 --> 00:23:25.580
a month at a time.

00:23:25.580 --> 00:23:29.790
And it's almost
my other city now.

00:23:29.790 --> 00:23:31.770
It used to be Los Angeles.

00:23:31.770 --> 00:23:38.660
And no one should be--
no one-- me should not

00:23:38.660 --> 00:23:42.410
be limited to one place
because the world is so full.

00:23:42.410 --> 00:23:44.030
And especially Europe.

00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:44.910
Now, wait a minute.

00:23:44.910 --> 00:23:45.847
Now, I'm in Europe.

00:23:45.847 --> 00:23:47.930
But when I was in London,
I'm no longer in Europe.

00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:50.160
That really sucks.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:51.200
I can't believe that.

00:23:51.200 --> 00:23:53.010
But I won't get into it.

00:23:53.010 --> 00:23:54.130
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Well, you're
definitely in Europe now.

00:23:54.130 --> 00:23:55.546
DANNY FIELDS: I
can't believe what

00:23:55.546 --> 00:24:00.605
it's done to my universe--
my London world.

00:24:00.605 --> 00:24:03.420
Because it's just wonderful,
brilliant people--

00:24:03.420 --> 00:24:07.180
artists and bar
owners and waitresses

00:24:07.180 --> 00:24:09.640
and busboys and whatever.

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:11.670
I can't believe what
it's done to them.

00:24:11.670 --> 00:24:14.050
This is like a shadow
over London this time.

00:24:14.050 --> 00:24:16.560
Someone threw something on them.

00:24:16.560 --> 00:24:20.180
There's this greatest,
wonderful city-- giant

00:24:20.180 --> 00:24:24.980
city-- in the world and
they're all, what happens now?

00:24:24.980 --> 00:24:26.084
This is kind of a tragedy.

00:24:26.084 --> 00:24:28.500
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: A lot of
people are very upset about it.

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:30.480
DANNY FIELDS: Too close to
it to even talk about it.

00:24:30.480 --> 00:24:31.950
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: So I
have one more question.

00:24:31.950 --> 00:24:33.915
So if you have a
question in the audience,

00:24:33.915 --> 00:24:37.340
you can start getting ready now.

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:40.900
So, 50 years in
the music industry.

00:24:40.900 --> 00:24:44.290
Who-- if you look around
today-- you talked about all

00:24:44.290 --> 00:24:46.466
of the artists and your
favorite artists earlier.

00:24:46.466 --> 00:24:48.090
If you looked around
today, would there

00:24:48.090 --> 00:24:49.560
be any artists
where you'd think,

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:51.815
god, I'd love to
have discovered them

00:24:51.815 --> 00:24:53.190
or I'd love to be
promoting them?

00:24:53.190 --> 00:24:54.310
DANNY FIELDS: Yeah.

00:24:54.310 --> 00:24:56.380
There's always going
to be songwriters

00:24:56.380 --> 00:24:58.510
and that's the most
important thing to me.

00:24:58.510 --> 00:25:02.290
But I can't name one
and it wouldn't be fair.

00:25:02.290 --> 00:25:08.540
I saw a band in London in an
almost empty bar in November

00:25:08.540 --> 00:25:10.952
in Camden, called False Heads.

00:25:10.952 --> 00:25:11.660
And I loved them.

00:25:11.660 --> 00:25:13.950
I just loved their energy
and they were rock and roll

00:25:13.950 --> 00:25:15.840
and we stayed friends.

00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:17.800
What I can do for
them, I don't know.

00:25:17.800 --> 00:25:20.625
I'm not in the
music business now.

00:25:20.625 --> 00:25:27.130
Of the people I've worked with,
we said before, I'm-- Nico.

00:25:27.130 --> 00:25:30.910
And now, I love--
everyone's going to hate me,

00:25:30.910 --> 00:25:33.800
I love electronic dance music.

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:39.692
And I love-- well, this is
how it happened, if I may.

00:25:39.692 --> 00:25:42.800
I go to a jam and
they play music.

00:25:42.800 --> 00:25:44.550
And it's usually
late at night and I

00:25:44.550 --> 00:25:46.090
work out and listen to music.

00:25:46.090 --> 00:25:47.920
And there's this great song.

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:49.350
I said, wow, what is the song?

00:25:49.350 --> 00:25:51.560
This is the number one hit.

00:25:51.560 --> 00:25:53.810
I'm kind of good at that.

00:25:53.810 --> 00:25:57.560
Not always, but kind of
good at spotting the hit.

00:25:57.560 --> 00:25:59.730
And I had to find
out who's playing,

00:25:59.730 --> 00:26:02.100
and it was a Spotify
fitness feed.

00:26:02.100 --> 00:26:02.750
OK?

00:26:02.750 --> 00:26:06.120
If you have a gym,
you can call Spotify

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:11.010
and say, send me fitness stuff--
music that we can put on.

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:14.140
And they can do bass
and drums or they

00:26:14.140 --> 00:26:18.970
can do '80s, like Cyndi Lauper.

00:26:18.970 --> 00:26:21.420
This was from the feed
called Tomorrowland.

00:26:21.420 --> 00:26:24.010
This was my first encounter
with Tomorrowland,

00:26:24.010 --> 00:26:28.119
which is a gigantic
and famous and-- how

00:26:28.119 --> 00:26:29.410
could I not know what this was?

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:31.120
Because I'm not 17.

00:26:31.120 --> 00:26:32.420
I didn't know what it was.

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:36.990
It's this franchise of new
electronic dance music.

00:26:36.990 --> 00:26:40.970
And these giant spectacles,
where the lights-- I mean,

00:26:40.970 --> 00:26:43.450
forget Van Gogh and
Rembrandt-- whoever

00:26:43.450 --> 00:26:47.140
is doing those lights-- whoa!

00:26:47.140 --> 00:26:48.000
This is an artist.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:49.620
This is so great.

00:26:49.620 --> 00:26:52.770
And then some guy's standing
on stage doing this.

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:55.510
Everyone's going crazy
and picking their arms

00:26:55.510 --> 00:27:00.130
up in the air because they
know that you can't move

00:27:00.130 --> 00:27:03.460
very far from side to side.

00:27:03.460 --> 00:27:04.230
They know that.

00:27:04.230 --> 00:27:07.019
They don't have to be
told and I love that.

00:27:07.019 --> 00:27:08.310
And much of the music is great.

00:27:08.310 --> 00:27:08.840
OK.

00:27:08.840 --> 00:27:13.210
This one song was
by Stromae, who

00:27:13.210 --> 00:27:16.490
is a Belgian-- half-Belgian,
half-- his father

00:27:16.490 --> 00:27:18.510
was killed in the
Rwandan massacre.

00:27:18.510 --> 00:27:21.090
How many people do you know
that you could say that about?

00:27:21.090 --> 00:27:23.075
Now, I don't know
him but, well--

00:27:23.075 --> 00:27:25.010
and his mother is Belgian.

00:27:25.010 --> 00:27:28.590
And he's unbelievably great.

00:27:28.590 --> 00:27:30.530
And he's got YouTubes.

00:27:30.530 --> 00:27:33.830
And then his YouTubes will
take you to Tomorrowland,

00:27:33.830 --> 00:27:41.070
where I saw Paul Kalkbrenner,
the Berlin genius.

00:27:41.070 --> 00:27:44.000
And I always get a, duh.

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:45.700
And I get a jaw, like what?

00:27:45.700 --> 00:27:48.890
And then last night, I
said, well, I like Avicii,

00:27:48.890 --> 00:27:50.180
and there's this groan.

00:27:50.180 --> 00:27:52.190
Oh, we want our money back.

00:27:52.190 --> 00:27:54.000
Well, you know, well,
I like "Wake Me Up."

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:54.610
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: You
like what you like.

00:27:54.610 --> 00:27:55.720
DANNY FIELDS: I mean,
what a great song.

00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:56.870
It's the number one song.

00:27:56.870 --> 00:27:58.840
That's all.

00:27:58.840 --> 00:27:59.932
It's the song.

00:27:59.932 --> 00:28:01.140
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Absolutely.

00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:01.750
OK.

00:28:01.750 --> 00:28:04.120
I'm going to open it
up now for questions.

00:28:04.120 --> 00:28:05.340
DANNY FIELDS: You hate
me because I said Avicii.

00:28:05.340 --> 00:28:06.930
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: No,
we don't hate you.

00:28:06.930 --> 00:28:08.138
Does anybody have a question?

00:28:14.266 --> 00:28:15.640
AUDIENCE: Hi,
Danny, how are you?

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:16.848
DANNY FIELDS: Can I use that?

00:28:16.848 --> 00:28:18.530
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Yeah.

00:28:18.530 --> 00:28:18.920
DANNY FIELDS: I
just want to see.

00:28:18.920 --> 00:28:20.586
AUDIENCE: You want
to try this, as well?

00:28:20.586 --> 00:28:22.010
This one, as well?

00:28:22.010 --> 00:28:24.010
I was just wondering--
looking back

00:28:24.010 --> 00:28:27.400
and one of my favorite
music ever, maybe,

00:28:27.400 --> 00:28:30.620
is like Detroit,
MC5, The Stooges.

00:28:30.620 --> 00:28:33.320
When that happened, it was,
like-- looking at the YouTube

00:28:33.320 --> 00:28:36.580
videos, for example-- it was
the most energetic thing,

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:38.770
even by today's standards.

00:28:38.770 --> 00:28:40.932
But then, after
that, became the--

00:28:40.932 --> 00:28:42.390
DANNY FIELDS: What's
your question?

00:28:42.390 --> 00:28:43.264
AUDIENCE: --the punk.

00:28:43.264 --> 00:28:44.040
Is that--

00:28:44.040 --> 00:28:45.290
DANNY FIELDS: I do this a lot.

00:28:45.290 --> 00:28:49.410
Because I know you guys want
to contribute questions.

00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:52.330
AUDIENCE: So what happened
to The Stooges and MC5

00:28:52.330 --> 00:28:53.280
when punk happened?

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:54.196
DANNY FIELDS: Oh, god.

00:28:54.196 --> 00:28:55.060
When punk happened?

00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:56.892
Well, there was no punk
when they happened.

00:28:56.892 --> 00:28:57.850
And they didn't happen.

00:28:57.850 --> 00:28:59.830
And they were both fired
by the record company

00:28:59.830 --> 00:29:01.880
that I signed them to.

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:05.270
Which, then, 60 years later,
said, well, we're so proud.

00:29:05.270 --> 00:29:07.850
This is the record company that
brought you these two bands,

00:29:07.850 --> 00:29:09.250
that they fired.

00:29:09.250 --> 00:29:14.250
So the lineage is so complex.

00:29:14.250 --> 00:29:17.170
I suggest you read,
"Please Kill Me"

00:29:17.170 --> 00:29:18.795
for the American side of it.

00:29:18.795 --> 00:29:23.280
And a book by John Robb
about punk in England.

00:29:23.280 --> 00:29:26.490
The Ramones, in fact,
met each other--

00:29:26.490 --> 00:29:29.140
because there had never
been four different kinds

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:31.780
of people-- because
they were Stooges fans

00:29:31.780 --> 00:29:35.050
in their high school in 1970.

00:29:35.050 --> 00:29:36.110
OK.

00:29:36.110 --> 00:29:38.910
That's how they bonded.

00:29:38.910 --> 00:29:41.250
It's kind of an answer
to your question--

00:29:41.250 --> 00:29:45.430
is that you-- something
becomes something else

00:29:45.430 --> 00:29:49.570
or comes into the mind and
consciousness of somebody else

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:52.070
who says, yes, we like
what they're doing.

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:53.760
Let's do it as they do.

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:56.520
The New York Dolls,
as well, which I wish

00:29:56.520 --> 00:29:59.890
had been part of my life,
but they're not, formally.

00:29:59.890 --> 00:30:02.940
Except I loved them
and they invented

00:30:02.940 --> 00:30:09.300
another universe that went
this way and it went that way.

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:12.950
And then it got called punk.

00:30:12.950 --> 00:30:17.250
I'm not sure by whom--
I'm not sure it works.

00:30:17.250 --> 00:30:19.720
Someone said, oh,
the New York Times

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:21.124
is doing a big story on punk.

00:30:21.124 --> 00:30:23.290
And the writer said, oh,
we'll get you an interview.

00:30:23.290 --> 00:30:28.500
But in three to five sentences,
tell me what you think punk is.

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:31.150
I said, if I can't do it in
more than three to five words,

00:30:31.150 --> 00:30:32.520
forget it.

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:34.340
And I haven't
picked them out yet.

00:30:34.340 --> 00:30:40.040
But I would say young-- don't
get up there and flop around--

00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:47.000
and stylish and
aggressive and fabulous.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:49.550
So that's punk.

00:30:49.550 --> 00:30:50.930
I don't know.

00:30:50.930 --> 00:30:53.440
That wasn't an answer to your
question, was it, at all?

00:30:53.440 --> 00:30:53.940
Come back.

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:54.870
Ask me a follow-up.

00:30:54.870 --> 00:30:57.120
AUDIENCE: It was pretty much
an answer to my question,

00:30:57.120 --> 00:30:58.275
all right.

00:30:58.275 --> 00:31:00.400
DANNY FIELDS: You can have
a follow-up because that

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:02.836
was such a terrible answer.

00:31:02.836 --> 00:31:05.771
I know it was.

00:31:05.771 --> 00:31:07.270
AUDIENCE: Do you
know-- for example,

00:31:07.270 --> 00:31:09.880
for MC5, it seems
like Wayne Kramer--

00:31:09.880 --> 00:31:13.330
all that energy--
he's been doing,

00:31:13.330 --> 00:31:15.530
now he's been to "Jail
Guitar Doors" thing, which

00:31:15.530 --> 00:31:18.070
is interesting and important.

00:31:18.070 --> 00:31:22.180
But I guess he just kind
of disappeared for a while.

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:22.930
DANNY FIELDS: Yes.

00:31:22.930 --> 00:31:25.270
He's great and he's here.

00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:26.950
And he's great.

00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:30.000
And he was-- it was his
energy, the first time I ever

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:36.210
saw the MC5 on stage at the
Grande Ballroom in Detroit--

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:39.310
September 22, 1968.

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:41.240
And don't ask me
how I remember that.

00:31:41.240 --> 00:31:41.820
But it was.

00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:44.020
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
That's impressive.

00:31:44.020 --> 00:31:49.890
DANNY FIELDS: Great, great,
great source of nuclear fusion.

00:31:49.890 --> 00:31:51.770
Something happening
there that is

00:31:51.770 --> 00:31:58.680
extra musical, that's beyond
chords and notes and yes.

00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:00.130
And Wayne is great.

00:32:00.130 --> 00:32:05.680
And the band, unfortunately,
got a little bit meh.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:08.580
Well, too political for a band.

00:32:08.580 --> 00:32:10.880
And this did in the
Sex Pistols, as well,

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:13.880
who are another
great band who were

00:32:13.880 --> 00:32:21.450
destroyed because no one
wants a band that's political.

00:32:21.450 --> 00:32:23.640
It is not wanted.

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:28.180
It's associated with destruction
and revolt and smashing

00:32:28.180 --> 00:32:28.880
and burning.

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:32.210
And it's unfortunate.

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:33.120
Next question.

00:32:33.120 --> 00:32:34.060
No, I'm sorry.

00:32:34.060 --> 00:32:34.597
We'll talk.

00:32:34.597 --> 00:32:35.430
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:32:35.430 --> 00:32:37.410
Yeah

00:32:37.410 --> 00:32:38.960
AUDIENCE: Actually, it's-- hi.

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:40.660
It's a follow-up on
what you just said.

00:32:40.660 --> 00:32:45.110
So '60s, as we read
from books and you saw,

00:32:45.110 --> 00:32:47.800
were also a time of
destruction and violence,

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:50.060
as well as a fight for
rights in the United States.

00:32:50.060 --> 00:32:53.910
A lot of great
discoveries and trouble.

00:32:53.910 --> 00:32:56.717
Much like what's going on
now in the United States.

00:32:56.717 --> 00:32:57.300
Do you think--

00:32:57.300 --> 00:32:59.341
DANNY FIELDS: I don't know
what you mean by that.

00:32:59.341 --> 00:33:01.830
Because what's going on in the
United States cannot be said

00:33:01.830 --> 00:33:03.145
in 20 words or less.

00:33:03.145 --> 00:33:04.020
AUDIENCE: Absolutely.

00:33:04.020 --> 00:33:10.480
DANNY FIELDS: And this is not
a Murdoch headline, so please--

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:14.530
AUDIENCE: Do you think
that this decade, with all

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:17.030
of the tumultuous
events, will bring us

00:33:17.030 --> 00:33:21.670
something as culturally
powerful as '60s did?

00:33:21.670 --> 00:33:24.180
DANNY FIELDS: Well, if I
could predict the future,

00:33:24.180 --> 00:33:25.770
I'd be so rich and
famous, I would not

00:33:25.770 --> 00:33:27.247
have to be sitting here now.

00:33:27.247 --> 00:33:28.163
AUDIENCE: But you are.

00:33:28.163 --> 00:33:28.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:28.910 --> 00:33:31.370
DANNY FIELDS: I would
buy more than one island.

00:33:31.370 --> 00:33:32.600
OK?

00:33:32.600 --> 00:33:33.430
I don't know.

00:33:33.430 --> 00:33:35.230
How can I know?

00:33:35.230 --> 00:33:36.760
You guys-- it's up to you.

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:38.460
I'm getting off this bus.

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:43.040
It's up to you to steer
it from now on, I hope.

00:33:43.040 --> 00:33:50.110
I'm sure there will be things
that we can't imagine now.

00:33:50.110 --> 00:33:53.870
That's Shakespeare's-- "more
things in heaven and earth than

00:33:53.870 --> 00:33:55.430
are in your philosophy."

00:33:55.430 --> 00:33:56.480
There are.

00:33:56.480 --> 00:33:58.730
And because there
are more of them,

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.380
it means we can't
give them a name

00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:04.990
and put them in a
directory or a folder.

00:34:04.990 --> 00:34:07.840
So I hope so and I believe so.

00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:12.770
Or else there's-- go to Facebook
and talk about what you ate

00:34:12.770 --> 00:34:13.800
for breakfast.

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:16.650
Or make the future.

00:34:16.650 --> 00:34:19.230
I think it's a choice.

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:21.800
That's a bad answer, too.

00:34:21.800 --> 00:34:24.690
It's hard to be simplistic
about these things,

00:34:24.690 --> 00:34:26.130
but I know what
you want to know.

00:34:26.130 --> 00:34:28.850
And I didn't make it.

00:34:28.850 --> 00:34:30.389
I came upon it.

00:34:30.389 --> 00:34:37.540
I came upon a mini
universe-- several of them--

00:34:37.540 --> 00:34:43.210
that was generating excitement,
art, talent, wonderfulness,

00:34:43.210 --> 00:34:45.949
songs, music, paintings, light.

00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:46.860
All that.

00:34:46.860 --> 00:34:47.850
Dance.

00:34:47.850 --> 00:34:49.179
All that.

00:34:49.179 --> 00:34:51.949
The future's going to be
putting them all together.

00:34:51.949 --> 00:34:57.150
That's why I like the EDM shows
because it's all one thing.

00:34:57.150 --> 00:35:02.112
I think that package is what
I'm really-- you will see.

00:35:02.112 --> 00:35:03.320
I probably won't live to see.

00:35:03.320 --> 00:35:05.490
But there will be that.

00:35:05.490 --> 00:35:07.740
I know that.

00:35:07.740 --> 00:35:11.400
Pass your plastic-- your sponge.

00:35:11.400 --> 00:35:12.280
Oh, OK.

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:13.643
It's been passed.

00:35:13.643 --> 00:35:14.430
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:14.430 --> 00:35:16.390
I was wondering--
I've read that you

00:35:16.390 --> 00:35:18.409
introduced Iggy Pop to Bowie.

00:35:18.409 --> 00:35:20.700
And I was wondering if you
could tell us a little bit--

00:35:20.700 --> 00:35:21.910
how'd that happen
or why did you--

00:35:21.910 --> 00:35:22.060
DANNY FIELDS: OK.

00:35:22.060 --> 00:35:23.310
I'll tell you how it happened.

00:35:23.310 --> 00:35:27.450
Because-- this is
not miraculous.

00:35:27.450 --> 00:35:30.410
There's no-- it sounds cosmic.

00:35:30.410 --> 00:35:31.402
Oh, my god.

00:35:31.402 --> 00:35:32.860
This meeting--
there must have been

00:35:32.860 --> 00:35:36.860
one god touching-- you know,
the Michelangelo's ceiling

00:35:36.860 --> 00:35:39.850
thing-- Adam's finger.

00:35:39.850 --> 00:35:42.460
It did not happen that way.

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:48.014
David had come to-- David
had-- we knew he was--

00:35:48.014 --> 00:35:49.555
we knew from reading
"Melody Maker"--

00:35:49.555 --> 00:35:55.780
we didn't really know him then,
that he loved Iggy's work.

00:35:55.780 --> 00:35:57.190
He loved Lou Reed.

00:35:57.190 --> 00:36:01.530
And he came to New York and
hooked up with Lisa and Richard

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:03.520
Robinson who put
out "Rock Scene"

00:36:03.520 --> 00:36:12.330
magazine and were widely
media-savvy in the '70s.

00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:18.990
And Iggy happened to be
staying at my flat in New York.

00:36:18.990 --> 00:36:21.830
And Lisa Robinson
called me and said,

00:36:21.830 --> 00:36:23.210
we just had dinner
with Lou Reed.

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:25.580
And now David wants to
meet Iggy and I heard--

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:27.290
isn't he staying with you?

00:36:27.290 --> 00:36:28.010
Yeah.

00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:28.700
He's sleeping.

00:36:28.700 --> 00:36:30.500
We'd just watched
some terrible Western

00:36:30.500 --> 00:36:32.210
and he was sitting on the couch.

00:36:32.210 --> 00:36:34.960
And [SNORES].

00:36:34.960 --> 00:36:36.010
Come to Max's.

00:36:36.010 --> 00:36:37.390
David wants to meet.

00:36:37.390 --> 00:36:40.300
Can you bring Iggy
to Max's Kansas City,

00:36:40.300 --> 00:36:44.955
which was the action
central hangout in New York.

00:36:44.955 --> 00:36:46.790
It was just around the corner.

00:36:46.790 --> 00:36:47.963
So, Iggy.

00:36:47.963 --> 00:36:48.830
Uhhh.

00:36:48.830 --> 00:36:49.810
I said, wake up.

00:36:49.810 --> 00:36:51.550
David Bowie wants to meet you.

00:36:51.550 --> 00:36:52.745
Uhhh.

00:36:52.745 --> 00:36:54.870
The one who said you were
his favorite new vocalist

00:36:54.870 --> 00:36:56.150
in "Melody Maker."

00:36:56.150 --> 00:36:57.579
Oh, OK.

00:36:57.579 --> 00:36:58.370
It's just at Max's.

00:36:58.370 --> 00:36:59.630
It's around the corner.

00:36:59.630 --> 00:37:00.640
Come on, wake up.

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:06.820
And so we walked the 200 or 300
yards there and it was late.

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:08.570
Almost-- there were
very few people there.

00:37:08.570 --> 00:37:10.210
It was around 3:00 AM.

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:18.420
And I said, Iggy, here's what
you asked to be delivered.

00:37:18.420 --> 00:37:21.980
And the two of them just
started talking about music.

00:37:21.980 --> 00:37:25.380
And Lisa and Richard
and I, who were

00:37:25.380 --> 00:37:29.270
responsible for this match,
went off in the corner

00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:33.770
and ordered a port or vodka
and just watched them.

00:37:33.770 --> 00:37:37.050
And yes, they seemed
to be getting along.

00:37:37.050 --> 00:37:37.840
That was it.

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:40.700
So I didn't do-- it
was not miraculous.

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:42.180
It was, you're a house guest.

00:37:42.180 --> 00:37:44.130
Get up, someone
wants to meet you.

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:45.280
That was it.

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:46.890
I had not plotted this.

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:51.240
Oh, some day, he
can-- because we

00:37:51.240 --> 00:37:53.240
didn't know who
he was, except we

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:56.040
thought he was great and
fabulous and beautiful.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:38:00.410
He was in New York
looking for his idols, who

00:38:00.410 --> 00:38:01.430
were Lou and Iggy.

00:38:01.430 --> 00:38:03.340
So that's all I did.

00:38:03.340 --> 00:38:04.180
Just, Iggy, come on.

00:38:04.180 --> 00:38:04.940
Let's go.

00:38:04.940 --> 00:38:07.160
Let's walk a few blocks.

00:38:07.160 --> 00:38:07.660
That's it.

00:38:07.660 --> 00:38:10.220
And it becomes legendary
and you want to know,

00:38:10.220 --> 00:38:11.520
what was really like?

00:38:11.520 --> 00:38:13.571
It was really like
[INTENTIONALLY MUMBLES]

00:38:13.571 --> 00:38:15.820
and they started talking
about music and we moved away

00:38:15.820 --> 00:38:17.747
and that was it.

00:38:17.747 --> 00:38:18.580
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:18.580 --> 00:38:20.330
DANNY FIELDS: Not--
there was not lighting

00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:22.360
and the Red Sea didn't part.

00:38:22.360 --> 00:38:22.860
Nothing.

00:38:22.860 --> 00:38:23.675
Just, that was it.

00:38:23.675 --> 00:38:25.050
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
I think we have

00:38:25.050 --> 00:38:26.400
time for one more question.

00:38:34.397 --> 00:38:35.230
AUDIENCE: Hi, Danny.

00:38:35.230 --> 00:38:36.396
Thanks a million for coming.

00:38:36.396 --> 00:38:38.480
It's really interesting
to hear you talk.

00:38:38.480 --> 00:38:39.970
I understand you worked
with The Doors, as well.

00:38:39.970 --> 00:38:42.011
I'd be curious to hear
how that relationship came

00:38:42.011 --> 00:38:44.198
about and even what
you did with The Doors.

00:38:44.198 --> 00:38:45.542
[DANNY SIGHS]

00:38:46.322 --> 00:38:47.030
AUDIENCE: Or not.

00:38:47.030 --> 00:38:47.710
Or talk about--

00:38:47.710 --> 00:38:49.376
DANNY FIELDS: Well,
no, I mean, it's OK.

00:38:49.376 --> 00:38:51.950
I mean, look.

00:38:51.950 --> 00:38:54.230
They were part of
my life because-- it

00:38:54.230 --> 00:38:56.960
was another accident.

00:38:56.960 --> 00:38:59.860
A woman I knew in Los
Angeles said oh, my band

00:38:59.860 --> 00:39:01.812
that I work with is
coming to New York.

00:39:01.812 --> 00:39:02.520
Will you do this?

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:04.010
She was doing me a favor.

00:39:04.010 --> 00:39:05.640
I had a band go
into Los Angeles,

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:07.670
she had a band come to New York.

00:39:07.670 --> 00:39:09.714
Would you check them out?

00:39:09.714 --> 00:39:11.630
See if there's anything
you could do for them?

00:39:11.630 --> 00:39:13.480
They could use a little press.

00:39:13.480 --> 00:39:15.985
I went to see them.

00:39:15.985 --> 00:39:19.850
At about the same time,
my greatest groupy

00:39:19.850 --> 00:39:25.740
gals-- I mean, the real
forefront of the-- that word

00:39:25.740 --> 00:39:27.260
is patronizing, I know.

00:39:27.260 --> 00:39:28.530
It's sexist, I know.

00:39:28.530 --> 00:39:31.810
But these girls knew
what was happening.

00:39:31.810 --> 00:39:34.070
And oh, he's the sexiest guy.

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:36.400
This great band playing uptown.

00:39:36.400 --> 00:39:37.400
I heard it from them.

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:41.486
Then I get to the person
who represents herself

00:39:41.486 --> 00:39:42.610
as the manager of the band.

00:39:42.610 --> 00:39:45.230
Would you go see them and
see if you can help them?

00:39:45.230 --> 00:39:46.510
So I went to see them.

00:39:46.510 --> 00:39:49.080
And went, well,
this is a good band.

00:39:49.080 --> 00:39:53.050
And I went to the rec-- and I
said-- I said I'm going, too.

00:39:53.050 --> 00:39:53.930
I'm your press agent.

00:39:53.930 --> 00:39:54.720
Hello.

00:39:54.720 --> 00:39:59.320
Your LA woman asked
me to help you here.

00:39:59.320 --> 00:40:01.200
OK, OK.

00:40:01.200 --> 00:40:04.690
This is 1967, I think.

00:40:04.690 --> 00:40:07.780
And I said, I'm going to come
and interview you and ask you

00:40:07.780 --> 00:40:09.950
and each of you-- you sit there.

00:40:09.950 --> 00:40:12.940
What's your favorite flower and
what do you look for in a girl?

00:40:12.940 --> 00:40:14.250
And all that.

00:40:14.250 --> 00:40:15.855
And that was the
beginning of that.

00:40:15.855 --> 00:40:17.230
And I went to the
record company.

00:40:17.230 --> 00:40:20.705
I said, hi, I'm your--
it was so different then.

00:40:20.705 --> 00:40:22.900
It was like a little village.

00:40:22.900 --> 00:40:23.720
OK.

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:27.410
And I'm the press agent for
your band called The Doors.

00:40:27.410 --> 00:40:29.760
Oh, wow, we never
met a press agent.

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:31.150
They never met a press agent.

00:40:31.150 --> 00:40:32.300
Come over.

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:37.260
And eventually, Elektra
hired me to just start

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:39.330
a press department for them.

00:40:39.330 --> 00:40:43.820
And so I found
myself, officially,

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:47.800
the publicity person for
this person who turned out

00:40:47.800 --> 00:40:51.090
to be an astonishing asshole.

00:40:51.090 --> 00:40:53.540
Although, one of the
most talented people

00:40:53.540 --> 00:40:54.580
I've ever known.

00:40:54.580 --> 00:40:56.290
And one of the smartest.

00:40:56.290 --> 00:40:59.360
And one of the meanest and
cruelest and most brilliant

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:02.350
and-- except for his poetry,
which is not very good.

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:06.310
Everything else
he did was, whoa.

00:41:06.310 --> 00:41:07.620
He was extra human.

00:41:07.620 --> 00:41:09.450
And you know he's
not really dead.

00:41:09.450 --> 00:41:11.463
That's a whole other thing.

00:41:11.463 --> 00:41:13.010
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:13.010 --> 00:41:16.350
I mean, there is a corpse
buried in Paris somewhere.

00:41:16.350 --> 00:41:21.110
But he's-- he keeps making
trouble like he did then.

00:41:21.110 --> 00:41:22.610
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
I think that's it.

00:41:22.610 --> 00:41:24.058
That's a great note to end on.

00:41:24.058 --> 00:41:25.540
DANNY FIELDS: OK.

00:41:25.540 --> 00:41:28.584
But I-- what can
I say about him?

00:41:28.584 --> 00:41:29.750
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: Brilliant.

00:41:29.750 --> 00:41:31.740
Listen, thanks so much
for being here today.

00:41:31.740 --> 00:41:32.210
DANNY FIELDS: Thank you.

00:41:32.210 --> 00:41:33.050
FIONNUALA MEEHAN: For
answering all of our questions.

00:41:33.050 --> 00:41:33.500
DANNY FIELDS: Thank you.

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:34.440
FIONNUALA MEEHAN:
For sharing so much.

00:41:34.440 --> 00:41:34.810
It was absolutely fascinating.

00:41:34.810 --> 00:41:36.430
DANNY FIELDS: Thank
you and thank you.

00:41:36.430 --> 00:41:38.260
Thank you.

